# M1

**Milestone 1: Requirements Specification**

**Team Name:** Kingfishers  
**Project Title:** Review Battle  
**GitHub Repository URL:** [KelvinnC/cosc310project](https://github.com/KelvinnC/cosc310project)

**1\. Software Requirements Specification and Documentation**

**1.1 Non-Functional Requirements**

| Quality | Description |
| :---- | :---- |
| Performance | The system shall respond to user actions (e.g., posting, viewing, or voting on reviews) within 5 seconds for 95% of requests under normal load conditions. |
| Scalability | The system shall support at least 100 concurrent users without performance degradation. |
| Security | The system shall allow multiple users to log in with unique usernames and passwords. |
| Usability | The UI shall be intuitive such that new users can complete core tasks with an error rate of less than 5% after 5 minutes of use. |
| Maintainability | The codebase shall be modular and have at least 80% test coverage. |
| Availability | When the Docker container is running, the system shall be accessible at least 90% of the time during testing sessions. |
| Portability | The system shall support all modern browsers. |
| Logging | The system shall log all transactions that occur on the site |
| Error Handling | The system shall display an error upon an invalid transaction |

**1.2 Functional Requirements**

**1.2.1 Informal / High-Level Functional Requirements**

| ID | Informal / High-Level Functional Requirement |
| :---- | :---- |
| HLFR-01 | Users can register and log in to the system using credentials |
| HLFR-02 | Users should be able to post, view, update, flag and delete reviews for movies. |
| HLFR-03 | Users can sort, filter, and download reviews in a structured format |
| HLFR-04 | Users can participate in ‘review battles’ to judge which review is funnier. |
| HLFR-05 | The system displays a leaderboard of the top-voted funniest reviews. |
| HLFR-06 | Users can search for and filter reviews by movie title and rating. |
| HLFR-07 | Users have personalized dashboards showing their reviews, favourited reviews, and active penalties. |
| HLFR-08 | Users can download their personal activity history showing voting, favourited reviews, active penalties and personal reviews. |
| HLFR-09 | Admins can mark inappropriate reviews as invisible and apply penalties (e.g., suspension or ban) to users who violate rules. |
| HLFR-10 | Admins have access to an admin dashboard for managing reviews, users, flagged reviews and penalties. |
| HLFR-11 | The system tracks and stores all votes, reviews, flags, and penalties using JSON files. |

| SSR-03 | The system shall allow new users to register with a username and password.  |
| SSR-04 | The system shall allow users to securely log in and out using static credentials stored in a JSON file. |
| SSR-05 | The system shall have two roles: admin and user. |
| SSR-06 | The system shall track votes from review battles. |
| SSR-07 | The system shall display the top winning reviews on a leaderboard, updating in real-time. |
| SSR-08 | The system shall allow users to favourite reviews to look at later. |
| SSR-09 | The system shall allow users to flag inappropriate reviews. |
| SSR-10 | The system shall allow administrators to penalize users for posting inappropriate reviews. |
| SSR-11 | The system shall allow users to post new reviews. |
| SSR-12 | The system shall allow users to delete their own reviews. |
| SSR-13 | The system shall allow users to download their review data in JSON format. |
| SSR-14 | The system shall allow users to filter reviews based on movie and funniness score. |
| SSR-15 | The system shall integrate with an external API to ensure that all movies are searchable |

**1.2.4 Acceptance Criteria** 

| ID | Acceptance Criteria |
| :---- | :---- |
| US-01 | A new user can register by providing a unique username and password.  Registration fails if the username exists already. User details are stored in the JSON credentials file. |
| US-02 | Users can only log in with valid credentials stored in the JSON file. An access and refresh token are provided to the user for secure use of the platform Users can log out, deleting stored refresh tokens |
| US-03 | Logged-in users can create a review by providing a movie title, review text, and rating Reviews must be between 50 and 1000 characters. Review is saved to the reviews JSON file. |
| US-04 | Users can edit reviews they created. The updated review replaces the old one in the JSON file. System shows confirmation after successful update. |
| US-05 | Users can delete reviews they created Deleted reviews are removed from the JSON file. The system shows confirmation after deletion. |
| US-06 | Users can view reviews associated with a specific movie by selecting that movie Reviews display the author, rating, and text. Reviews load within 5 seconds. |
| US-07 | Users can flag any review as inappropriate by clicking a flag icon Flagged reviews appear in the admin dashboard for review Users cannot flag the same review more than once. |
| US-08 | Admin dashboard shows a list of flagged reviews. Each flagged review displays the movie, author, and reason for flag. Admin can sort flagged reviews by time or frequency of flags. |
| US-09 | Admin can mark a review as “invisible.” Invisible reviews no longer appear for regular users. Admin receives confirmation when invisibility is applied. |
| US-10 | Admin can suspend or ban a user. Suspended/banned users cannot log in. Suspension/ban status is stored in the JSON file. |
| US-11 | Users can search for movies by title. Search results display all reviews for the movie. Search is case-insensitive and returns partial matches. |
| US-12 | Users can sort movies by rating (ascending/descending). Sorting applies to all movies in the system. Sorted results are displayed within 5 seconds. |
| US-13 | The system selects two reviews at random for a battle. Users can vote for one of the two reviews. Users cannot vote more than once per battle. The vote is stored in the JSON file. |
| US-14 | Users can see the number of votes their own reviews have received. Scores update in real time after new votes are cast. |
| US-15 | The leaderboard shows the top reviews ranked by votes. Leaderboard updates dynamically as new votes are cast. The Leaderboard displays at least the top 10 reviews. |
| US-16 | Admin can view a dashboard summarizing active penalties, and user accounts. Admin can hide/delete reviews and suspend/ban users from the dashboard. Changes take effect immediately and dashboard updates dynamically. |
| US-17 | All actions are persistently stored in a structured format. Stored data accurately reflects system activity. Data persists across logouts and system restarts. |
| US-18 | Users can download reviews, votes, and leaderboard data in JSON format. Downloads complete successfully and contain all requested information. |
| US-19 | System logs flagged content for admin review. Hidden / “Invisible” content is applied consistently across all pages and never shown to regular users. |
| US-20 | User can filter reviews by numerical rating Reviews can be sorted by highest or lowest rating Reviews can be sorted by movie |

**1.2.5 Domain Requirements** 

| ID | Requirement |
| :---- | :---- |
| DR-01 | Each review battle shall involve exactly two reviews, and the system shall prevent a user from voting on the same battle more than once. |
| DR-02 | The system shall ensure that the reviews in a battle are not authored by the voting user. |
| DR-03 | Votes in review battles are weighed equally. |
| DR-04 | Reviews must be between 50 characters and 1000 characters in length. |
| DR-05 | Users only post one review per movie. |
| DR-06 | Reviews must be associated with a valid movie in the system database. |
| DR-07 | Only admins can remove flagged reviews or penalize users. |
| DR-08 | Leaderboard displays reviews based on votes from review battles, showing only visible reviews. |
| DR-09 | All review and vote data must be stored in JSON format. |
| DR-10 | User credentials shall be stored in a JSON file with static passwords. |
| DR-11 | Users can only search for movies present in the system database. |
| DR-12 | Search filters can be applied in combination (e.g., by rating, title, or genre).  |
| DR-13 | The system shall enforce two roles: admin and user, with access control applied to all features. |
| DR-14 | Reviews marked as invisible shall not appear in user-facing lists, dashboards, review battles, or the leaderboard. |

**Team Name:** Kingfishers

## **1\. Introduction**

## **1.1 Purpose**  This document outlines an architectural and design plan for the *Review Battle* system. It provides a structured representation of the system’s organization, including its overall architecture, components, data flows, classes, interactions, and key sequences. It describes how the system meets the requirements defined in Milestone 1, and serves as a reference for developers during implementation.

### **1.2 Scope** The *Review Battle* system allows users to securely register and log in (HLFR-01; NFR: Security), post, view, update, delete, and flag reviews for movies (HLFR-02), and sort, filter, and download reviews in a structured format (HLFR-03). Users can participate in competitive “battles” to judge which review is funnier, and reviews are ranked on a live leaderboard based on votes (HLFR-04, 05). Users can search for and filter reviews by movie title and rating (HLFR-06), view a personalized dashboard showing their reviews, favourited reviews, and active penalties (HLFR-07), and download their personal activity data, including their reviews, favourited reviews, votes, and penalties (HLFR-08). Administrators can hide reviews and apply penalties to users who violate rules (HLFR-09), and view an admin dashboard for managing users, reviews, flagged reviews, and penalties (HLFR-10). The system tracks and stores all votes, reviews, flags, and penalties in JSON files to provide persistent storage and ensure consistent behaviour across sessions (HLFR-11; NFR: Logging). The system is designed to be performant, scalable, secure, usable, maintainable, available, and portable (NFRs), with error logging and handling to ensure reliable operation and a user-friendly experience (NFRs: Logging, Error Handling).

## 

## 

## **2\. High-Level Architecture**

### **2.1 Architecture Overview** ![][image1]

### **2.2 Architectural Style and Rationale** The *Review Battle* system will utilize a Model-View-Controller (MVC) architectural style: 

- ### Model represents the system’s data and business logic, enforcing workflows required to allow the system to meet requirements. 

- ### View will handle the user interface (UI). It formats the information provided by the Model for the user.

- The controller acts as the intermediary between the model and the view. It will receive and validate user input, call the appropriate model methods to update data or handle business logic, and update the view with results returned by the model.


MVC works well for the *Review Battle* system because it separates data, business logic, and UI, making interactions between components simpler and cleaner.   
The model ensures all rules are enforced consistently across interactions and defined in the same place, minimizing the risk of duplicating or bypassing business logic (NFR: reliability). This ensures enforcement of requirements like those for user validation, review updates, deletion, and restrictions, review selection for battles, votes and leaderboard updates, and penalties  (HLFR-01, 02, 03, 07, 09). This separation also supports maintainability, because components can be developed and tested independently, and security, as access to data and operations is controlled (NFRs: maintainability, security).   
The view is responsible for clearly presenting information from the model to the user. It handles the UI, including personalized dashboards (HLFR-07), review lists (HLFR-02, 03, 06), review battles (HLFR-04), the leaderboard (HLFR-05), and the admin dashboard (HLFR-10). Separating the View from the business logic allows changes to be made to the UI without affecting data and rules defined by the Model (NFR: maintainability).  
The controller is responsible for communicating between the model and the view, managing user interactions and commanding system behaviour. The controller handles processing user registration and login (HLFR-01), creating, updating, deleting, and flagging reviews (HLFR-02), managing review battles and votes (HLFR-04), and updating the leaderboard (HLFR-05, 07). By centralizing the flow of data between the view and model, the controller ensures consistent application behaviour, minimizes duplication, and simplifies testing, improving maintainability, reliability, and performance (NFRs: maintainability, reliability, performance).

## **4\. Design Patterns** 

### **4.1 Applied Pattern(s)**

We will use Singleton to implement a logger. We intend to ensure there is exactly one logging object coordinating to write to logs.json, which is accessible throughout the entire system.

![][image7]

### **4.2 Justification**

A singleton works in our system for a variety of reasons. Since we have many controllers (ie Auth, Review, Battle, Moderation, Export) that emit logs, the singular logger ensures that there won’t be concurrent writes that corrupt the logs.json while centralizing all file handling and buffering. Furthermore, the centralization of a logger ensures that all the JSON lines are uniform, which makes exports and downstream analysis predictable. Resource use is also accounted for, as creating and wiring a logger per request is wasteful, and the singleton can reuse the same resources across the whole system.

With frequent API controllers logging events (auth attempts, review edits, vote casts, etc.), there is a need for coordination or else we’d risk failure across the system, such as duplicate file formats, file contention, and even race conditions. As such, the singleton allows a single open descriptor to logs.json, a shared formatter, and a lock around file appends.

# Project Requirements

# **The Project**

## **Overview**

Students will design and implement a full-stack multiuser system using modern software engineering practices. The system should demonstrate proper architecture, modularity, and testing. The system will avoid the use of traditional databases. Instead, data will be stored and managed using JSON or CSV files.

The goal is to give students hands-on experience with both backend and frontend development, CI, Control version system, testing, and containerization.

## **Dataset**

Each team should select one of the following datasets. These datasets serve as a starting point, and we expect each team to expand and enhance their chosen dataset.

* **IMDB Movies User Reviews**: [**https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/sadmadlad/imdb-user-reviews**](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/sadmadlad/imdb-user-reviews)  
* [**Links to an external site.**](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/karkavelrajaj/amazon-sales-dataset)

## **General Requirements**

The project must include the following characteristics and functionalities:

1. Backend: Implemented using FastAPI (Python).  
2. Frontend: Implemented using: Next.js.  
3. Data Storage: Use JSON or CSV files (no database).  
4. API Communication: The backend should expose a RESTful API that the frontend consumes.  
5. Testing: Use Pytest for backend testing.  
6. Multiuser System: Must support multiple users interacting with the system concurrently.  
7. Version Control & Collaboration: Git \+ GitHub (branches, issues, pull requests, reviews).  
8. Continuous Integration: GitHub Actions (automated testing on push/pull requests).  
9. Containerization: Use Docker for both frontend and backend.  
10. The project must implement correct and consistent business logic that aligns with the system’s domain rules and requirements.  
11. Software Engineering Principles: Follow the SOLID principles.  
12. Apply general software engineering best practices (e.g., modularity, readability, maintainability, documentation).

 

## **Backend Requirements**

### **The backend should:**

* Data Management:  
  * Load, parse, and persist data using CSV/JSON files.  
    * **Stores user info, review info**  
  * Provide data operations like Create, Read, Update or Delete on data items  
    * **CRUD on reviews**  
  * Allow download of structured JSON files customized by the users.  
    * **Download all reviews**  
* RESTFUL API endpoints (The list of API points can be longer):  
  * Retrieve all items.  
    * **Retrieve all reviews**  
  * Retrieve a single item by ID  
    * **Retrieve a review by ID (or maybe a “battle” by ID)?**  
  * Sort, search, and filter items based on at least 2 attributes.  
    * **Sort based on movie, or “score”**  
  * Add a new item  
    * **Add a new review to the database**  
  * Update existing items  
    * **Update your own review**  
  * Delete existing items  
    * **Delete your own review**  
* User System  
  * Support multi-user authentication using static JSON files (no external authentication service).  
  * Role-based access (admin vs regular users). Admins have elevated privileges for managing data, monitoring activity, and applying penalties.  
    * **Delete inappropriate reviews, monitor votes**  
  * Role-specific dashboards, users should be directed to a Dashboard customized to their role  
    *   
  * Users should be able to complete at least 4 distinct transactions within the system. Examples of transactions are: Renting, Booking, Ordering, and Saving a resource. TA should approve the transactions.  
    * **Voting on a review**  
    * **Posting a review**  
    * **Flagging a review as inappropriate for admin**  
    * **Posting a movie**  
    * **Favouriting a review**  
    * **Editing a review**  
  * Admins should be able to apply penalties to users when they fail to meet specific rules or criteria (e.g., late return of an item, overuse of system resources).  
    * **Penalty for posting an inappropriate review: suspension, ban**  
    * **Penalty for posting a fake movie: suspension, ban**  
  * Penalties should be stored in the system and reflected in the user’s dashboard (e.g., “1 active penalty – late return of item X”).  
* Integration with external systems  
  * Use an external API and integrate it in your system. The external API should be discussed and approved by the TAs  
  * **tmdb**

 

### **The frontend should:**

* The front end should be simple  
* It must provide clear pathways for users to find, search, and interact with the resources or items they need  
* Admins should have a dedicated interface that allows them to efficiently manage data, monitor activity, and apply administrative actions (e.g., penalties, edits, or deletions)

 

## **Additional Requirements**

Collaboration & Process

* Teams must work in a GitHub repository with:

  * Clear branching strategy.

  * Pull requests with reviews.

  * Use of GitHub Projects/Issues for task management.

* Each team must record and document Scrum meetings (e.g., sprint planning, sprint reviews, and retrospectives).

Documentation

* A README.md explaining how to build/run the project.  
* API documentation   
* Scrum documents should be stored in a dedicated folder named **`/scrum-documents`** within the team’s repository. These document should include:

  * Date and type of meeting.  
  * Attendees.  
  * Key discussion points.  
  * Action items and responsibilities.  
* Testing documents should be stored in a dedicated folder named **`/testing-documents`**

 

Testing & Quality

* CI pipeline runs tests automatically.  
* Unit tests  
* Integration tests  
* E2E tests  
* Testing coverage should be added into the folder **`/testing-documents`**
